by this performance,
not being reassured by hearing
him say, contrary

22:05.958 --> 22:10.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to all evidence, that this is a
well-functioning
machine that they're seeing in
the beginning

22:10.329 --> 22:12.164 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of this administration.

22:12.198 --> 22:16.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Kansas Secretary
of State Kris
Kobach, was this a reassuring
news conference

22:16.302 --> 22:18.170 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or something else?

22:18.204 --> 22:20.706 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KRIS KOBACH (R), Kansas
Secretary of State:
I think, to many conservatives,
many Republicans,

22:20.739 --> 22:24.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it was reassuring, in the sense
that this
was the first time we have seen
a president,

22:24.310 --> 22:30.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a conservative president, really
express vocally
at a press conference the bias
he feels and

22:30.950 --> 22:36.388 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
many of us feel has been given
in the coverage
toward the Trump administration.

22:36.422 --> 22:41.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so he's sort of holding the
press' feet
to the fire while he's taking
their questions.

22:41.126 --> 22:42.928 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it's combative.

22:42.962 --> 22:44.697 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's interesting.

22:44.730 --> 22:47.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think you are going to see a
lot more people
turning in to these press
conferences.

22:47.433 --> 22:51.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It used to be that conservatives
who were
in government, like myself, we
would get what

22:51.470 --> 22:54.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
