42:50.067 --> 42:55.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The sheriff says people like
Jimenez won't
trust police if they're
constantly afraid

42:55.072 --> 42:56.607 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of being deported.

42:56.641 --> 42:58.509 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And Jimenez agrees.

42:58.543 --> 43:01.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FELIX JIMENEZ, Undocumented
Immigrant (through
translator): We're afraid when
we see a police

43:01.846 --> 43:02.880 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
officer.

43:02.914 --> 43:04.048 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We're Hispanic.

43:04.081 --> 43:06.217 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We could be stopped for any
reason.

43:06.250 --> 43:10.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The real fear that keeps me
nervous after
a long day is that I may not see
my children

43:10.888 --> 43:13.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because I was stopped for only a
small infraction.

43:13.458 --> 43:18.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SALLY HERNANDEZ: We cannot
afford to make
our communities less safe by
driving people

43:18.830 --> 43:20.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
into the shadows.

43:20.665 --> 43:24.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Sheriff
Hernandez won her
election promising to take this
very action,

43:24.268 --> 43:30.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but her critics have pounced,
saying she's
created Texas' first sanctuary
city, and deriding

43:30.041 --> 43:31.876 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
her as Sanctuary Sally.

43:31.909 --> 43:33.177 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

43:33.211 --> 43:35.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GREG ABBOTT (R), Texas: We will
ban sanctuary
cities in Texas.

43:35.413 --> 43:37.148 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

43:37.181 --> 43:40.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Texas Governor
Greg Abbott
accused the sheriff of betraying
her oath,

43:40.251 --> 43:44.288 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
calling her argument frivolous,
shortsighted
and dangerous.

43:44.322 --> 43:50.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In retaliation, the governor
started cutting
$1.5 million in grants to Travis
County.

43:50.194 --> 43:52.930 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They fund things like drug
courts and domestic
violence prevention.

43:52.964 --> 43:53.931 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

43:53.965 --> 43:54.932 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GREG ABBOTT: We are seeking
fines.

43:54.966 --> 43:56.901 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We are seeking to withdraw more
state funds.

43:56.934 --> 44:01.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are seeking court orders that
compel these
officials like this sheriff to
comply with

44:01.706 --> 44:04.509 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the law or possibly go to jail
themselves.

44:04.542 --> 44:09.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Austin is now
among dozens
of so-called sanctuary cities
across the U.S.

44:09.814 --> 44:14.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While there's no official
definition for a
sanctuary city, the term
generally means local

44:14.719 --> 44:19.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
police aren't turning in every
undocumented
immigrant to federal
authorities.

44:19.857 --> 44:23.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These cities have long drawn the
ire of President
Trump.

44:23.127 --> 44:25.830 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
During the campaign, he
threatened all of
them.

44:25.863 --> 44:29.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Block funding for
sanctuary
cities.

44:29.734 --> 44:31.002 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We block the funding.

44:31.035 --> 44:32.303 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
No more funding.

44:32.336 --> 44:35.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: A promise he
kept soon after
taking office.

44:35.706 --> 44:37.608 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But mayors are pushing back.

44:37.642 --> 44:41.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTY WALSH (D), Mayor of
Boston, Massachusetts:
We will not be intimidated by
the threat to

44:41.279 --> 44:43.014 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
fed funding.

44:43.047 --> 44:44.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAHM EMANUEL (D), Mayor of
Chicago: I want
to be clear: We're going to stay
a sanctuary

44:44.115 --> 44:45.883 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
city.

44:45.917 --> 44:48.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BILL DE BLASIO (D), Mayor of New
York: We
are going to defend all of our
people, regardless

44:48.352 --> 44:52.223 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of where they come from and
regardless of
their documentation and status.

44:52.256 --> 44:57.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Back in Texas,
state legislators
are trying to pass a law making
it illegal

44:57.328 --> 45:00.765 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for any city or county to limit
cooperation
with ICE.

45:00.798 --> 45:05.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: We are in a dangerous path
as a society,
so that's what this bill does
for

45:05.503 --> 45:09.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Senate Bill 4
would require
counties to determine the
immigration status

45:09.774 --> 45:15.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of everyone in their custody, as
well as honor
all requests from federal
immigration officials

45:15.379 --> 45:17.114 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to detain people indefinitely.

45:17.148 --> 45:22.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: We just won't criminals
who are here
illegally and committing crimes
to stay in

45:23.020 --> 45:24.322 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
our state.

45:24.355 --> 45:26.390 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Both sides
testified about
the proposed law.

45:26.424 --> 45:30.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: I do believe your bill is
unconstitutional,
on its face, actually.

45:30.962 --> 45:34.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: State Senator
Charles Perry
introduced Senate Bill 4.

45:34.999 --> 45:40.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The bill says state officials
who fail to
comply with the law would face
criminal prosecutions

45:40.204 --> 45:41.606 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and hefty fines.

45:41.639 --> 45:43.541 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLES PERRY (R), Texas State
Senator: These
are attention-getters.

45:43.574 --> 45:47.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These are, we're going to be
serious about
uniform, consistently without
prejudice, applying

45:47.678 --> 45:49.447 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the law to everyone.

45:49.480 --> 45:53.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, how do
local police
interact with federal
immigration officers?

45:53.317 --> 45:57.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Right now, when someone is
arrested in any
location in the U.S., they're
fingerprinted,

45:57.588 --> 46:02.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their name is checked against
several databases,
and information is shared
electronically with

46:02.159 --> 46:03.995 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
immigration officials.

46:04.028 --> 46:06.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DENISE GILMAN, University of
Texas Law School:
There is a federal provision
that requires

46:06.430 --> 46:10.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
local jurisdictions to provide
information
to the federal immigration
authorities.

46:10.701 --> 46:11.736 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: That's the law
nationwide?

46:11.769 --> 46:12.770 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DENISE GILMAN: That's right.

46:12.803 --> 46:13.971 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And everybody is complying with
that.

46:14.005 --> 46:15.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's really no question about
that.

46:15.906 --> 46:19.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Denise Gilman
is an immigration
law professor at the University
of Texas in

46:19.543 --> 46:21.379 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Austin.

46:21.412 --> 46:24.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DENISE GILMAN: The next step
then is, what
does ICE decide to do, the
federal immigration

46:24.982 --> 46:26.951 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
authorities?

46:26.984 --> 46:32.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If ICE decides to request that
the local jurisdiction
hold onto somebody for
additional time, they

46:32.790 --> 46:34.792 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
file what's called a detainer.

46:34.825 --> 46:38.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the courts and the federal
government
have recognized that that's
really just a

46:38.596 --> 46:40.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
request to local jurisdictions
to hold...

46:40.865 --> 46:42.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It's not a
legally binding
contract.

46:42.466 --> 46:44.301 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DENISE GILMAN: It's not a legal
binding contract.

46:44.335 --> 46:48.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: If immigration
officials
come to you and ask for and give
you one of

46:48.939 --> 46:52.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these detainers and say, we'd
like you to
hold these 10 people, why not
just hold all

46:52.943 --> 46:54.712 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
10 of them?

46:54.745 --> 46:59.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SALLY HERNANDEZ: We are treating
immigration
like we do any other law
enforcement agency.

46:59.350 --> 47:04.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if somebody from another
county calls
me up and says, you have
somebody in your

47:04.789 --> 47:08.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
custody, hold them for me, I
would ask them,
do they have a warrant?

47:08.693 --> 47:10.761 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And if they have a warrant, we
will hold them.

47:10.795 --> 47:12.296 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Why is that
warrant important?

47:12.329 --> 47:15.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SALLY HERNANDEZ: Because that
warrant is based
on probable cause.

47:15.399 --> 47:20.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Sheriff
Hernandez says she
will honor detainer requests in
cases of murder,

47:20.571 --> 47:22.840 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
sexual assault and human
trafficking.

47:22.873 --> 47:27.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Otherwise, she is not legally
required to
hold people without warrants.

47:27.078 --> 47:31.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Other jurisdictions have been
sued for doing
exactly that, for violating
constitutional

47:31.882 --> 47:33.651 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
due process.

47:33.684 --> 47:36.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if you're within the border
of the U.S.,
regardless of where you're from,
where you're

47:36.954 --> 47:39.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
born or what your status is, the
Constitution
protects you?

47:39.990 --> 47:41.792 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DENISE GILMAN: That's right.

47:41.826 --> 47:45.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And especially when it comes to
fundamental
constitutional principles like
liberty, that

47:45.496 --> 47:49.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is a fundamental constitutional
principle
that is guaranteed to all
persons within the

47:50.000 --> 47:52.470 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
United States, regardless of
immigration status.

47:52.503 --> 47:58.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: SB-4, the law
that would
in effect outlaw sanctuary
cities statewide,

47:58.542 --> 48:02.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has left many immigrant families
like Felix
Jimenez's on edge.

48:02.680 --> 48:07.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He lives with his wife, Brenda,
who is also
undocumented from Mexico, and
their daughter,

48:07.284 --> 48:11.555 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Evelyn, born in the United
States, and a citizen.

48:11.589 --> 48:14.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He believes undocumented people
need to speak
out.

48:14.458 --> 48:18.229 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He recently attended this rally
against SB-4.

48:18.262 --> 48:22.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Up until a few months ago, Felix
says he felt
he could call the police for
help, like when

48:22.600 --> 48:25.102 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he was robbed and left bloody on
the street

48:25.136 --> 48:29.540 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
FELIX JIMENEZ (through
translator): I called
the police and they helped me.

48:29.573 --> 48:31.175 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I was hospitalized.

48:31.208 --> 48:32.543 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I had X-rays done.

48:32.576 --> 48:35.613 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I was in a lot of pain, and it
still hurts.

48:35.646 --> 48:39.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if that law existed, I
wouldn't be able
to report the crime because of
my status.

48:39.650 --> 48:45.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, what do
you say to someone,
not just Sheriff Hernandez, that
having local

48:45.723 --> 48:53.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
police be a quasi-extension of
immigration
enforcement makes their
communities less safe,

48:53.564 --> 48:54.532 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not more safe?

48:54.565 --> 48:55.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHARLES PERRY: Yes.

48:55.566 --> 48:57.535 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think, one, that's a
dangerous logic.

48:57.568 --> 49:02.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we're going to not adhere to
the law in
the name of applying the law.

49:02.740 --> 49:06.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, logically, that doesn't
reconcile with
me.

49:06.277 --> 49:10.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Last week,
Perry's bill
passed the Texas Senate and will
be debated

49:10.681 --> 49:13.984 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the House.

49:14.018 --> 49:16.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Governor Abbott has promised to
sign it.

49:16.353 --> 49:20.825 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
When it passes, Sheriff
Hernandez's department
could be running against the
law.

49:20.858 --> 49:25.095 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, in the meantime, Hernandez
has been getting
what she asked for.

49:25.129 --> 49:30.401 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ICE officials have been
providing warrants
to hold people, and her office
is honoring

49:30.434 --> 49:31.735 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
them.

49:31.769 --> 49:38.209 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
William Brangham
in Austin, Texas.

49:38.242 --> 49:47.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally, another
installment
in our Brief But Spectacular
series.

49:47.885 --> 49:53.757 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Namwali Serpell is a
Zambian-born writer and
associate professor of English
at the University

49:53.791 --> 49:55.626 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of California, Berkeley.

49:55.659 --> 50:01.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her first novel, "The Old
Drift," comes out
next year, but, here, she
describes her own

50:01.432 --> 50:03.234 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
story.

50:03.267 --> 50:06.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NAMWALI SERPELL, Author: There
are all these
different terms for what an
immigrant is in

50:06.370 --> 50:10.107 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
America, when you have the
permission to stay.

50:10.140 --> 50:13.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's permanent resident,
there's resident
alien.

50:13.544 --> 50:18.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Immigration officials are really
funny with
me, because they look at my
permanent resident

50:18.916 --> 50:20.684 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
card.

50:20.718 --> 50:24.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm always very anxious
about this when
I'm at the -- I mean, will they
let me back

50:24.321 --> 50:25.489 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in?

50:25.522 --> 50:29.326 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Can I still be here?

50:29.360 --> 50:33.364 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I teach American literature.

50:33.397 --> 50:39.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I start out all of my
courses by saying,
you might be wondering why a
Zambian citizen

50:39.803 --> 50:44.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and a resident alien of the
United States
is teaching you the history of
American literature.

50:44.875 --> 50:48.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But who better than an outsider
to teach you
about American literature?

50:48.779 --> 50:56.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All of the great literature of
the U.S. is
told through the story of an
outsider, Nick

50:56.086 --> 50:59.323 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Carraway in "Gatsby" or Humbert
Humbert in
"Lolita."

50:59.356 --> 51:03.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Being on the outside or being an
alien is
the condition of being American.

51:03.060 --> 51:10.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's a way to see the
country from within,
but also with a different
perspective.

51:10.034 --> 51:13.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I remember when my parents told
me we were
moving to the States.

51:13.971 --> 51:16.040 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My sisters and I were really
excited.

51:16.073 --> 51:20.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For me, at age 8, it was a
pretty intense
shift.

51:20.077 --> 51:24.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I had kids kind of making fun of
me, making
fun of my hair, making fun of my
accent.

51:24.848 --> 51:32.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I remember very specifically a
kid asking
me in the cafeteria in fifth
grade, what are

51:32.089 --> 51:37.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you, not, who are you, and not
what race are
you, but what are you?

51:37.561 --> 51:40.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And what she meant was, are you
black or white?

51:40.664 --> 51:43.834 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I asked my dad, my white father,
who's a psychologist.

51:43.867 --> 51:45.936 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He said: "You're a citizen of
the world.

51:45.970 --> 51:47.171 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You are human."

51:47.204 --> 51:49.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that answer was very
unsatisfactory.

51:49.907 --> 51:56.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was only in college that I
really started
to say I'm black, because, in
America, I'm

